## How This Works

When you ask Claude to "remember" something, it gets saved as a separate file in this directory and linked here.

### Memory Types

| Type | What It Stores | Example |
|------|----------------|---------|
| **user** | Your role, background, preferences, knowledge | "I'm a backend engineer who prefers Python" |
| **feedback** | Corrections or validated approaches | "Don't use mocks in integration tests" |
| **project** | Ongoing work, goals, or context | "We're in a feature freeze until June 20" |
| **reference** | Pointers to external resources | "Bugs are tracked in Linear project INGEST" |

### Memory Lifecycle

```
User: "Remember that I prefer detailed explanations"
  ↓
Claude saves: user_explanation-style.md
  ↓
Claude updates: MEMORY.md (adds a link)
  ↓
Future sessions: Claude reads MEMORY.md → loads all linked memories
```

---

## Quick Reference

| What You Say | What Claude Does |
|--------------|-----------------|
| "Remember that [preference]" | Saves a new memory file and links it here |
| "Forget about [thing]" | Removes the memory file and its link |
| "What do you remember about me?" | Reads all memories and summarizes them |
| "Save this as a skill" | Exports a pattern to `~/.claude-confessor/skills/` |
| "Update my profile" | Edits `user-profile.md` with new information |

---

## Maintenance

- **Stale memories:** If a memory becomes outdated, ask Claude to update or remove it
- **Duplicate memories:** Claude should merge or consolidate duplicate entries
- **Organization:** Memories are organized by type (user, feedback, project, reference)
- **Search:** Ask Claude "What memories do I have about [topic]?"

